Score for this alignment: 1301

The two sequences aligned above are each influenza A viruses from the giant anteater
(top) and the penguin (bottom), and each are around 850 base pairs. They were 
obtained from the influenza virus database. 

The most optimal pairing for these strands, as shown by the instruction string result, 
was simply to shift  the entire top strand 8x, and then never add bases for the rest of 
the strand (until the very end). This would suggest that the genetic material of viruses 
that infect each animal is actually quite similar, and that they likely evolved very 
recently (on an evolutionary timescale) from a common ancestor, especially given the 
remarkably high alignment score of 1301. 

I decided to do a control test on the first 860 base pairs of a random human Y 
chromosome, and the penguin virus used earlier. The Y-Chromosome was obtained here:
https://www.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/nuccore/NC_000024.10

These results are WAY different! This shows that arbitrary shifting does not easily make
DNA sequences match, because the algorithm returned a much poorer alignment for
random sequences than for similar viruses. The lower alignment score confirms our 
earlier statement that the influenza viruses between the anteater and the penguin were
similar, given that a y chromosome and a penguin's flu virus are dissimilar.
